Squats

Squats help develop the lower body and isometrically work the core. The body is lowered until the knees are at least 90 degrees before rising. Squats that stop at 90 degrees and those that go beyond can be called Parralel Squats and Deep Squats respectively.

Push-Ups

Push-ups are a well known and commonly practised exercise with a lot of variantions and progressions. During the exercise a person pushes about 60% to 75% of their body mass. The exact amount depending on how high or low one currently is in the exercise.

If you often find yourself sagging at the hips or otherwise fail to keep the body as a straight line you may need to strengthen your core muscles. The plank is an excellent exercise for focusing on this as it puts you in the same position a push-up.

Diamond Push-Ups

Like the push-up but with the hands closer together and the index fingers and thumbs of both hands touching each other. This puts greater stress on the tricep muscles that regular push-ups.

Explosive Push-Ups

A push-up performed with enough force to lift the palms of the floor.

Archer Push-Ups

Putting increasingly more weight on one arm increases both the strength required and developed by the exercise.

One-Arm Push-Ups

This exercise can put as much as 70% of one's bodyweight on one-arm.

The feet are often shoulder width apart for this exercise. The closer together the feet the more difficult the exercise. Some people consider doing this exercise with the feet completely together and no twisting of the a body a 'Perfect one-arm push-up'.

Clap Push-Ups

A push-up performed with enough force to lift the hands entirely of the floor. The body must rise high enough that there is enough time to clap the hands and replace them on the floor.

Flying Superman Push-Ups

Aztec Push-Ups

Wall Push-Ups

A simpler variation of the push-up.

Knee Push-Ups

A simpler variation of the push-up.

Incline Push-Ups

A more difficult variation of the push-up. Also targets the pecs from a different angle than the regular push-up.

Knuckle Push-Ups

A variation of the push-up that is performed on the knuckles. Puts less stress on the wrist so can be used as an alternative in case of wrist pains. Also used in various combat sports to harden the knuckles.

Maltese Push-Ups

Dragon Flag

In addition to being a core exercise the dragon flag is also a pulling exercise. In fact a lack of pulling strength, not core strength, may prove to be a limiting factor with this exercise.

Plank

An isometric exercise for developing the core in which one holds a push-up position for extended times. The exercise can also be performed on the forearms. Remember to engage the core and keep breathing during the exercise.

One-Arm Plank

By using only one arm it becomes more difficult to maintain stability forcing the muscles to work harder.

Straight Leg Ab Wheel

By using only one leg and arm the muscles are forced to work harder to maintain stability.

Pull-Ups

An exercise for developing the upper body. It uses a overhand/pronated grip where the palms face away from the body.

Archer Pull-Up

Putting increasingly more weight on one side increases both the strength required and developed by the exercise.

One-Arm Pull-Up

High One-Arm Pull-Up

L-Sit Pull-Up

Assuming a l-sit moves more of the body's weight to the front. This decreases the leverage of the weight forcing the muscles to work harder.

Pull-Up Negative

A negative is performed by jumping up to the top position of a pull-up and slowly lowering yourself. This is a great way to develop the strength required to perform the regular/concentric pull-up. As a rule of thumb or goal assume that being able to perform seven negatives pull-ups of 10 seconds each means you can now perform one regular pull-up.

Chin-Ups Negative

A pull-up with a underhand/supinated grip where the palms face towards the body. A negative is performed by jumping up to the top position of a chin-up and slowly lowering yourself. This is a great way to develop the strength required to perform the regular/concentric chin-up. As a rule of thumb or goal assume that being able to perform seven negatives chin-ups of 10 seconds each means you can now perform one regular chin-up.

Chin-Ups

A pull-up with a underhand/supinated grip where the palms face towards the body. This works the biceps more than a regular pull-up.

Typewriter Pull-Up

Rows

A pulling exercise that is sometimes recommended for developing the strength required to perform a pull-up. However the row also develops the scapular muscles in a way the pull-up does not.

This exercise can also be performed with a sturdy table if there is no suitable horizontal bar present.

Archer Row

Shifting more weight onto one side improves the strength required for and developed with the exercise.

One-Arm Row

Shifting more weight onto one side improves the strength required for and developed with the exercise.
